'''Partage''', from the French word "partager" meaning “to share,” was a system put in place to divide up ownership of excavated artifacts during the early part of the 20th century.<ref name=Cuno />  This system was mostly notably employed in [[Egypt]], [[Iraq]], [[Turkey]] and [[Afghanistan]].

Under ''partage'', foreign-led excavation teams provided the expertise and material means to lead excavations and in return were allowed to share the finds with the local government’s archaeological museums. It was through this system that the collections of archaeological museums at the [[University of Chicago]], the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and [[Harvard]] and [[Yale]] Universities were built up. Important parts of the collections of the [[British Museum]], the [[Brooklyn Museum]]<ref name=CultureGrrl>{{cite web|last=Rosenbaum|first=Lee|title=Brooklyn’s In-Your-Face Antiquities Policy|url=http://www.artsjournal.com/culturegrrl/2008/01/brooklyns_inyourface_antiquiti.html|work=CultureGrrl|accessdate=7 October 2013|date=January 30, 2008}}</ref> and the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]<ref name="Campbell 2010">{{cite news|last=Campbell|first=Thomas P.|title=Museum as Archaeologist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/29/opinion/l29met.html|accessdate=7 October 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 28, 2010}}</ref> also came through ''partage''.<ref name=Cuno>{{cite book|last=Cuno|first=James|title=Who Owns Antiquity? Museums and the Battle over Our Ancient Heritage (New in Paper).|year=2010|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton|isbn=1400839246|edition=[Pbk. ed.].}}</ref>  It was also how the collections in archaeological museums in Egypt, Iraq, Afghanistan, and Turkey were built up. According to [[James Cuno]], "Foreign museums underwrote and led scientific excavations from which both the international archaeological and local political communities benefited."<ref name=Cuno />

Many people{{who|date=April 2015}} believe that the ''partage'' system should be reinstated as a way of encouraging exchange and international education while still giving source countries authority over their cultural heritage.<ref name=Cuno /><ref name="Atwood 2008">{{cite journal|last=Atwood|first=Roger|title=Insider: Guardians of Antiquity?|url=http://archive.archaeology.org/0807/etc/insider.html|work=Archaeology|publisher=Archaeological Institute of America|accessdate=7 October 2013|volume=61 |issue=Number 4, July/August 2008}}</ref>

