==18th century==

{| class="wikitable" width="100%"
! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event
|-
| 1702 || || In Europe [[telescope]]s are used to aid in the aiming of artillery.{{sfn|Needham|1986|p=413}}
|-
| 1715 || || [[Jean Maritz]] introduces the horizontal drilling technique for casting cannons, increasing their reliability and accuracy while reducing the amount of metal needed for the barrel.{{sfn|Chase|2003|p=201}}
|-
| 1718 || || [[James Puckle]] invents the [[Puckle gun]], a [[breech-loading weapon|breech loading]] [[flintlock]] with a revolving set of chambers capable of firing 63 shots in seven minutes.{{sfn|Needham|1986|p=410}}
|-
| 1720 || || France establishes Europe's first national artillery school.{{sfn|Kinard|2007|p=107}}
|-
| 1725 || || [[Flintlock]] firearms completely displace [[matchlock]]s in Europe.{{sfn|Needham|1986|p=429}}
|-
| 1742 || || [[Benjamin Robins]] invents the [[ballistic pendulum]], which provides the first way to accurately measure the velocity of a bullet.{{sfn|Robins|1742}}
|-
| rowspan="2" valign="top" |  1750 || || [[Firearm]]s overtake the [[composite bow]] in cost, ease of use, range, and rate of fire, making mounted [[horse archer]]s completely obsolete.{{sfn|Roy|2015|p=9}}
|-
| || A [[detent]] is added to [[flintlock]]s to prevent the sear from catching in the half-cock notch.{{sfn|Phillips|2016}}
|-
| 1755 || || [[Naval guns]] are outfitted with [[flintlocks]]{{sfn|Kinard|2007|p=115}}
|-
| 1759 || || "[[Carronades]]" appear.{{sfn|Kinard|2007|p=116}}
|-
| 1770 || || A [[roller bearing]] is added to [[flintlock]]s to reduce friction and produce more sparks.{{sfn|Phillips|2016}}
|-
| 1780 || || A waterproof pan is added to [[flintlock]]s.{{sfn|Phillips|2016}}
|-
| 1783 || || [[Sir William Congreve, 1st Baronet]] improves gunpowder production by constructing dedicated testing ranges, new [[saltpeter]] refineries, and special proving houses. He also discovers "cylinder powder", gunpowder produced using [[charcoal]] sealed in iron cylinders, which is twice as powerful as traditional gunpowder and less likely to spoil, giving [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] gunpowder a reputation as best in the world.{{sfn|Andrade|2016|p=252}}
|-
| 1790 || || England begins fielding [[block trail carriage]]s, invented by [[Sir William Congreve, 1st Baronet]], the most advanced artillery transport of the time.{{sfn|Kinard|2007|p=109}}
|-
| 1799 || 22 April || Iron-cased [[Mysorean rockets]] are deployed by the [[Kingdom of Mysore]] against the [[East India Company]].{{sfn|Needham|1986|p=518}}
|}

